Investors in the Nigerian equities market recorded a week-on-week (W-o-W) gain of N73 billion, despite report negative sentiment in four of the five trading days. Capital market analysts noted that sentiments remained weak in the domestic market amidst rising COVID-19 cases in the country as well as persisting FX illiquidity. However, a one-off gain on Thursday, driven by a surge Dangote Cement, led the domestic bourse to its largest weekly gain in seven weeks. Thus, the All-Share- Index (ASI) advanced by 140.07 points or 0.58 per cent W-o-W to close 24,427.73 points. Also, market capitalisation rose N73 billion to close at N12.743 trillion. However, the rise in the general index eclipsed the negative performance of most sub-sector gauges as only the NSE Industrial index rose, by 0.60 per cent to close at 1,106.55 points amid positive financial results posted by Dangote Cement. The NSE Oil/Gas index, NSE Insurance index, NSE Banking index and the NSE Consumer Goods index declined by 4.67 per cent, 0.80 per cent, 0.62 per cent and 0.38 per cent respectively to close at 182.20 points, 122.34 points, 270.41 points and 404.25 points respectively. Market breadth for the week was positive as 28 equities appreciated in price, 25 equities depreciated in price, while 110 equities remained unchanged. Fidson Healthcare led the gainers’ table by 18.11 per cent to close at N3.13, per share. Unity Bank followed with a gain of 15.56 per cent to close at 52 kobo, while Royal Exchange went up by 14.18 per cent to close to 31 kobo per share. On the other side, Prestige Assurance led the decliners’ table by 14.81 per cent to close at 46 kobo, per share. International Breweries followed with a loss of 10.53 per cent to close at N3.40 and SEPLAT Petroleum Development Company (SEPLAT) declined by 10 per cent to close at N347.40, per share. Overall, a total turnover of 1.350 billion shares worth N14.433 billion in 16,723 deals were traded last week by investors on the floor of the Exchange, in contrast to a total of 1.016 billion shares valued at N7.436 billion that exchanged hands previous week in 18,092 deals. In the new week, analysts at Cowry Asset Management Limited expected investors to rejig their portfolios by buying shares of companies that post positive results and have sound fundamentals. Analysts at GTI Securities Limited said,“As investors await more earnings results, expect further bearish sentiment from the active investors in the coming week. However, extra price decline of fundamentally-viable stocks could drive more long-term investors to the market.”